Cell["\<\
In a typical Wolfram Notebook interface, you can just select what you want to \
iconize, and use the right-click menu. You\[CloseCurlyQuote]ll see an \
iconized form, but it\[CloseCurlyQuote]s the code \
\[OpenCurlyDoubleQuote]underneath\[CloseCurlyDoubleQuote] the icon that\
\[CloseCurlyQuote]ll actually be used. \
\>", "Text",
 Editable->False,
 Deletable->False,
 ShowCellBracket->False],

Cell["\<\
It\[CloseCurlyQuote]s also often convenient to use iconization when you want \
to include lots of data in a notebook, but don\[CloseCurlyQuote]t want to \
show it explicitly. \
\>", "Text",
 Editable->False,
 Deletable->False,
 ShowCellBracket->False],

Cell["\<\
Create a table of a thousand primes, but show it only in iconized form:\
\>", "CodeCaption",
 Editable->False,
 Deletable->False,
 ShowCellBracket->False],

